context: The first mention of the name "Rajasthan" appears in James Tod's <a0_0><b5_0>1829<b5_0/><a0_0/> publication <a1_0>Annals and Antiquities of Rajast'han or the Central and Western Rajpoot States of India<a1_0/>, while the earliest known record of <b6_0>"<a2_0>Rajputana<a2_0/>"<b6_0/> as a name for the region is in George Thomas's <a3_0>1800<a3_0/> memoir Military Memories. <a4_0>John Keay<a4_0/>, in his book <b7_0>India: A History<b7_0/>, stated that "Rajputana" was coined by the British in <b8_0>1829<b8_0/>, John Briggs, translating Ferishta's history of early Islamic India, used the phrase <b9_0>"Rajpoot (Rajput) princes"<b9_0/> rather than "Indian princes".
